column12: Sample_treatment_protocol_ch1
column13: Sample_growth_protocol_ch1
column15: Sample_extract_protocol_ch1
column40: Alignment and identification of open chromatin regions The data was processed following the recommendations of the ENCODE consortium (The ENCODE Consortium, n.d.)
column41: Coverage files Individual coverage files per replicate normalized for differences in sequencing depths between the different samples were generated with bamCoverage of the deepTools suite (Ram√¨rez et al. 2016) using the following parameters

column12: Cells were treated with vehicle (DMSO) or 1uM kinase inhibitor for 12 hours in complete culture media prior to collection
column13: Cells were seeded at 50% confluence in 100mm tissue culture plates. 24 hours following plating, cells were used for experiments
column15: Culture media was removed, cells were washed 1X with cold PBS/2% FBS and then removed using TrypLE. Samples were processed using the Omni-ATAC protocol (MR Corces, et al.) by the WCM Epigenomics Core, NEB Nextera kit using the original ATAC-seq library prep protocol (JD Buenrostro, et al.) by the WCM Epigenomics Core, balanced block design
column40: Reads were aligned to the human reference genome (version GRCh38) with BWA-backtrack (Heng Li and Durbin 2009). Post-alignment filtering was done with samtools and Picard tools (Li et al. 2009, Broad Institute (2015)) to remove unmapped reads, improperly paired reads, non-unique reads, and duplicates. To identify regions of open chromatin represented by enrichments of reads, peak calling was performed with MACS2 (Liu 2014). For every replicate, the narrowpeak results of MACS2 were used after filtering for adjusted p-values smaller than 0.01.

For every replicate, the narrowpeak results of MACS2 were used after filtering for adjusted p-values smaller than 0.01.
